The '''Atiu swiftlet''' or '''Sawtell's Swiftlet''' ('''''Aerodramus sawtelli''''') is a species of [[bird]] in the [[Swift (bird)|swift]] family, [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Atiu]] in the [[Cook Islands]].

This small, dark swift measures {{convert|10|cm|in|abbr=on}} long. It is sooty-brown above, slightly lighter below.<ref name=BirdLife/>

Its natural [[habitat]]s are the island's fernlands and mixed horticultural areas over which it feeds, and in makatea limestone caves within which it nests.<ref name=BirdLife/> The species is known on Atiu as kopeka.

Unlike all other swiftlets, it echolocates only through single clicks, rather than a mix of single- and double clicks.<ref>{{Citation |last=Brinkløv |first=Signe M. M. |title=Echolocation in Bats, Odontocetes, Birds, and Insectivores |date=2022 |url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-97540-1_12 |work=Exploring Animal Behavior Through Sound: Volume 1 |pages=419–457 |access-date=2023-09-09 |place=Cham |publisher=Springer International Publishing |isbn=978-3-030-97538-8 |last2=Jakobsen |first2=Lasse |last3=Miller |first3=Lee A.}}</ref>

